One efficient way which I can think of(provided you&#39;re using `Java 8` or later) is the use of ***[`streams api`](https://www.baeldung.com/java-8-streams)*** which are especially designed to be more efficient for operations on large data sets.

```java
List&lt;String&gt; domains = ...
String email = &quot;bob@gmail.com&quot;;

boolean domainMatches = domains.stream()
    .anyMatch(email::contains);

return !domainMatches;
```

Also, as pointed out by *@AndyTurner*, you shouldn&#39;t use `contains` because it can match some invalid address(like `bob@gmailcom`). So if you&#39;re looking for another way, you can use equals:

```java
List&lt;String&gt; domains = ...
String email = &quot;bob@gmail.com&quot;;

String domain = email.split(&quot;@&quot;)[1];

boolean domainMatches = domains.stream()
    .anyMatch(domain::equals);

return !domainMatches;
```

- **[Reference 1](https://dzone.com/articles/java-performance-for-looping-vs-streaming)**
- **[Reference 2](https://www.baeldung.com/java-streams-vs-loops)**

***EDIT:(Recommended approach)***

Based on the comments and after brainstorming I came up with yet another way which is more efficient that using `streams` as well and that is using a `HashSet`. Something like:

```java
List&lt;String&gt; domains = ...
String email = &quot;bob@gmail.com&quot;;

Set&lt;String&gt; domainSet = new HashSet&lt;&gt;(domains);
String domain = email.split(&quot;@&quot;)[1]; // You can also use indexOf and substring.

boolean domainMatches = domainSet.contains(domain);

return !domainMatches;
```

&gt; _&quot;... I would like the quickest way to check that the email has not got one of these domains in Java. ...&quot;_

The _fastest_ solution would be a _loop_.

```java
List&lt;String&gt; domains = ...
String email = &quot;bob@gmail.com&quot;.toLowerCase(),
       s = email.substring(email.indexOf(&#39;@&#39;) + 1);

Boolean domainsMatch = false;

//Some code to check the domains against the email

for (String domain: domains)
{
    if (domain.endsWith(s)) {
        domainsMatch = true;
        break;
    }
}

return domainsMatch;
```

Alternately, use a _stream_.

```java
List&lt;String&gt; domains = ...
String email = &quot;bob@gmail.com&quot;.toLowerCase(),
       s = email.substring(email.indexOf(&#39;@&#39;) + 1);

//Some code to check the domains against the email

Boolean noMatch
    = domains.stream()
             .noneMatch(x -&gt; x.toLowerCase().endsWith(s));
```

The [jmail library][1] could do this for you.  Rather than using regex to validate emails, it parses the email into [an object][2] and then conducts validation on the parts.  It also allows custom validation.  

One of the fields of in `Email.java` is `List&lt;String&gt; domainParts`.  This contains all the parts of the domain split by the period (assuming that it parsed properly, otherwise it will fail other validations).  You can add a custom validator to the `EmailValidator` as follows:
```java
public class MyEmailValidator {
  public boolean validateEmail(String email) {
    List&lt;String&gt; invalidDomains = List.of(&quot;gmail&quot;, &quot;yahoo&quot;);
    EmailValidator validator = JMail.strictValidator().withRule(validationEmail -&gt; Collections.disjoint(validationEmail.domainParts(), invalidDomains));
    return validator.isValid(email);
    }
}
```

You can test this easily enough.
```java
@Test
void validateEmail() {
  MyEmailValidator validator = new MyEmailValidator();
  assertTrue(validator.validateEmail(&quot;test@my.company.com&quot;));
  assertFalse(validator.validateEmail(&quot;test@gmail.com&quot;));
}
```


  [1]: https://github.com/RohanNagar/jmail
  [2]: https://github.com/RohanNagar/jmail/blob/master/src/main/java/com/sanctionco/jmail/Email.java

