answers.body_markdown:
Your design is already ready. What you need is a custom Deserializer for it. As linked on the comments here is a good article [Custom Deserialization](https://www.baeldung.com/jackson-deserialization#on-mapper)

Translating that article into a piece of code it would be something like (**note** this might not be workable, use as reference as I did not test it):

```
public class MessageDeserializer extends StdDeserializer&lt;Message&gt; {

    public MessageDeserializer() {
        super(Message.class);
    }

    @Override
    public Message deserialize(JsonParser jp, DeserializationContext ctxt) {
        try {
            JsonNode node = jp.getCodec().readTree(jp);
            Message message = new Message();

            // your known fields
            message.setAppId(node.get(&quot;appId&quot;).asText());
            message.setAction(node.get(&quot;action&quot;).asText());
            // .... other fields

            Entity entity = new Entity();
            entity.setMarketId(node.get(&quot;entity&quot;).get(&quot;marketId&quot;).asText());
            entity.setPropertyId(node.get(&quot;entity&quot;).get(&quot;propertyId&quot;).asText());
            // .... other fields

            Map&lt;String, Object&gt; otherFields = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
            JsonNode entityNode = node.get(&quot;entity&quot;);
            final List&lt;String&gt; knownEntityFields = List.of(&quot;marketId&quot;, &quot;propertyId&quot; /*, others here*/);
            entityNode.fields().forEachRemaining(entry -&gt; {
                String fieldName = entry.getKey();
                if ( knownEntityFields.stream().noneMatch(fieldName) ) {
                    otherFields.put(fieldName, entry.getValue());
                }
            });
            entity.setOtherFields(otherFields);

            message.setEntity(entity);
            return message;
        } catch (IOException e) {
            throw new RuntimeException(e);
        }
    }
}
```

You can even make it better by using reflection (some might disagree :) )

&gt; _&quot;... But how do I deal with the optional fields in the message? They&#39;re flat siblings of the ID and name fields, not a nested map ...&quot;_

If the field names are dynamic, just use a _[Map](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Map.html)_.

Here is an example using _[Gson](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gson)_.

```java
class Entity {
    public String marketId;
    public String propertyId;
    public String name;
    Map&lt;String, Object&gt; m;
}
```

```java
String s
    = &#39;{&#39;
    + &quot;    \&quot;appId\&quot;: \&quot;MyApp\&quot;,&quot;
    + &quot;    \&quot;action\&quot;: \&quot;Upsert\&quot;,&quot;
    + &quot;    \&quot;entityType\&quot;: \&quot;Property\&quot;,&quot;
    + &quot;    \&quot;entity\&quot;: {&quot;
    + &quot;        \&quot;marketId\&quot;:   \&quot;abc123\&quot;,&quot;
    + &quot;        \&quot;propertyId\&quot;: \&quot;def456\&quot;,&quot;
    + &quot;        \&quot;name\&quot;:       \&quot;Grand Central Station\&quot;,&quot;
    + &quot;        \&quot;hasFoo\&quot;:     true,&quot;
    + &quot;        \&quot;hasBar\&quot;:     false,&quot;
    + &quot;        \&quot;areaInSf\&quot;:   30000&quot;
    + &quot;    }&quot;
    + &#39;}&#39;;
Gson g = new Gson();
JsonElement e = g.fromJson(s, JsonElement.class);
Message m = g.fromJson(e, Message.class);
e = e.getAsJsonObject().get(&quot;entity&quot;);
m.entity.m = g.&lt;Map&lt;String, Object&gt;&gt;fromJson(e, Map.class);
m.entity.m.remove(&quot;marketId&quot;);
m.entity.m.remove(&quot;propertyId&quot;);
m.entity.m.remove(&quot;name&quot;);
```

This will work without deserializer kung fu:


```
public class Entity extends HashMap&lt;String, Object&gt; {
    public String getMarketId() {
        return get(&quot;marketId&quot;);
    }
    public String getPropertyId() {
        return get(&quot;propertyId&quot;);
    }
    public String getName() {
        return get(&quot;name&quot;);
    }
}
```

The rest of the attributes can be found in `keySet()` or `entrySet()` etc.

