Thanks to **@Turing85**, I came up with the following (potential) solution. I tested it and it works. All I need is for the rest of the team to accept it. This solution is for JUnit4, but what I could see should be very similar if using JUnit 5.

In simple terms:

 1. Annotate your test class with `@RunsWith(Parameterized.class)`
 2. Create a static method to create your test data (Parameters)
 3. Annotate such static method with `@Parameterized.Parameters`
 4. In my case, since I only need a single parameter (map), the return type for my `data()` method will be `Object[]` or `Iterable&lt;? extends Object&gt;`
 5. Your test class constructor should take the same arguments used in the `data()` method. If the returned array or iterable object contains more than one element, the test method will iterate as many times as the returned object has elements. For the example below, `myTest()` method will execute twice: once for `map1` and once for `map2`. If this is not desirable, you can return an iterable object containing a single element.

A simplified version of this solution should look like this

```
@RunsWith(Parameterized.class)
public class MyTestClass {
  private Map&lt;String, String&gt; valueMap;
  
  public MyTestClass(Map&lt;String, String&gt; valueMap) {
    this valueMap = valueMap;
  } 

  @Parameterized.Parameters
  public static Object[] data() {
    Map&lt;String, String&gt; map1 = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
    Map&lt;String, String&gt; map2 = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
    map1.put(&quot;foo&quot;, &quot;test1&quot;);
    map2.put(&quot;bar&quot;, &quot;test1&quot;);
    return new Object[] {map1, map2};
  }
  
  @Test
  public void myTest() {
    // DO YOUR TEST... for now, just show values in console
    valueMap.forEach((k,v) -&gt; System.out.println(&quot;Key: &quot;  k + &quot;; Value: &quot; + k));
  }
}
```
If you require a more involved example, the [Parameterized][1] class contains Javadoc with multiple examples. Ultimately, following those examples were extremely informative and complimented very well the link that @Turing85 provided in the Question comments section.


  [1]: https://junit.org/junit4/javadoc/4.12/org/junit/runners/Parameterized.html

